@article{Perala19901,
abstract = {The reproductive processes and environmental requirements for regenerating Betula alleghaniensis, B. papyrifera, B. pendula, and B. pubescens are reviewed. Their taxonomy is confusing because somatic chromosome number varies within species, and natural hybridization is common. Paper birch and the Eurasian birches are typical species of the boreal forest, whereas yellow birch grows no farther north than 49°, from Manitoba and Minnesota eastward across North America, and somewhat farther south than paper birch. Birches do not tolerate shade, except that seedlings prosper best at about half of full sunlight, and can endure up to 90% shade. Long photoperiods are required for genetic sources from high latitudes and from high altitudes. Growth is optimum at about 18°-22°C soil and air temperatures. The birches do not use water efficiently and are sensitive to both drought and flooding. They require fertile sites for best growth and are particularly sensitive to available soil phosphorus. The response of birch to soil chemistry is genetically variable. The birches improve soils by cycling nutrients efficiently, conveying oxygen to the rooting profile, and improving soil structure and permeability. The Eurasian birches from mycorrhizal relationships with many symbionts that markedly improve growth and survival. The mycorrhizal relationships of the North American birches are meagerly documented. Birch roots adapt to difficult conditions. Roots proliferate in the upper soil, but sinkers penetrate deep soil and restrictive layers. Rootlets develop best in organic matter and penetrate decayed wood. Birch seedlings typically grow only about 1 dm tall the first year, so they are easily suppressed by faster-growing and allelochemic vegetation. Many animals, large and small, can hinder regeneration by browsing seedlings or eating seed. Fire can easily kill mature birch, but prepares good seedbeds. Surviving birches produce stress seed crops and coppice to enable regeneration. The birches begin producing seed when 10-15 years old. Seed quality is usually higher in years with warm springs and abundant flowering. The seed ripens in late summer to early autumn and disperses mostly within a few months. Less than 10% of the seed is dispersed farther than 100 m. Birch seed can retain some viability in the forest floor for up to 3 years. The birch seed-coat contains a germination inhibitor that can be neutralized by stratification or by light. Germination is generally best at about 20°-30°C and under blue-green to red wavelengths. Undisturbed litter seedbeds are too hot and dry, and physically hinder birch germination and establishment. Seedlings establish best on disturbed seedbeds consisting of mixed mineral soil and organic matter, decayed wood in particular. Burned-over humus seedbeds are overly hot and dry, and may require several years before they can support birch seedlings. In contrast, peat or Sphagnum seedbeds may remain receptive for many years. {\textcopyright} 1990.},
