@book{Kemppainen201287,
abstract = {Mycorrhiza is the most ancient and widespread mutualistic symbiotic association between plants and soil borne fungi. Mycorrhizae sensu lato are dual organs of absortion formed by mutualistic symbiotic fungi inhabiting healthy absorbing organs such as roots, rhizomes or thalli of most terrestrial plants and also many aquatics and epiphytes. In nature the soil nutrient acquisition of plants occurs to great extent via these mycorrhizal organs. It is now widely accepted that mycorrhizae would have played a fundamental role in the colonization of the land by plants functioning as nutrient absorbing structures even before the appearance of roots. Mycorrhizae are traditionally classified into categories on the basis of their fungal partners and macro-and microscopical anatomical structures of the dual organs. Among them ectomycorrhiza (ECM) is typically formed between the fine roots of trees of boreal and temperate forest and fungal species usually belonging to Basidiomycota and Ascomycota. In this chapter we discuss the evolutionary origin of ECM, some of its morphological and anatomical characters, the ecological significance of ECM and some of the molecular traits related to establishment and functioning of ECM structures between fungi and their plant hosts. {\textcopyright} 2012 Nova Science Publishers, Inc. All rights reserved.},
