@article{Peintner199665,
abstract = {In the course of the interdisciplinary research program "Studies of ecosystems in the Limestone Alps- Achenkirch Altitude profiles", the basidiomycetes of different forest types were studied extensively for three years. The goal of the now presented investigation was to gather basic data regarding the actual state of mycocoenosis (qualitative and quantitative) in this area. The number of species, their abundance as well as their productivity, were recorded over the period of July 1991 to November 1993 in 6 plots situated in the area of Achenkirch (Tyrol, Austria): a subalpine spruce forest, a subalpine mixed forest, two beech woods, a Pinus stand and a ski slope. Altogether 466 basidiomycetes species were recorded, and classified in the following three main ecological groups: symbiontic mycorrhizal species, parasites and decomposers of soil, litter and wood. Special attention was taken also to the occurrence of Aphyllophorales which often are neglected in comparable studies. 133 corticoid, poroid, hydnoid and clavaroid basidiomycetes belonging to the Aphyllophorales were identified. Differences between the mycobiota of the three forest types are evident in regard of species diversity, productivity and abundance. The highest species diversity and abundance was found in the subalpine spruce forest with more than 300 fungal taxa. In the beech forests more than 200 basidiomycetes species were recorded, whereas only low species diversity was found in the Pinus stand (37 species) and on the slope (29 species). Dominant and characteristic species for each forest type are proposed and compared.},
